Title: THE BUILD
Credit: Written by
Author: The Developer
Draft date: 2025-04-22
Contact:
    clawscreenwriter.app

===

FADE IN:

EXT. COFFEE SHOP - DAY

Rain streaks the windows of a hipster coffee shop in Seattle. Inside, JORDAN (28, intense, laptop stickers covering every inch) hunches over a MacBook Pro, surrounded by empty espresso cups.

Jordan's fingers fly across the keyboard. Lines of code scroll past on the screen.

                    JORDAN
          (muttering)
      Final Draft costs how much? Three 
      hundred dollars? For software that 
      looks like it's from 2003?

Jordan slams the laptop shut, looks around the coffee shop.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
          (to no one in particular)
      I can build something better. In a 
      weekend.

The BARISTA (22, tattooed, unimpressed) looks over.

                    BARISTA
      You say that every week, Jordan.

                    JORDAN
      This time I mean it. A screenplay 
      editor that actually looks good. 
      Professional. Like the movies.

Jordan opens the laptop again. The screen glows blue against their face.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      I'm calling it... ClawScreenwriter.

                    BARISTA
      Because?

                    JORDAN
      Because I'm clawing my way out of 
      subscription hell.

Jordan cracks their knuckles. This is happening.

FADE TO:

INT. JORDAN'S APARTMENT - NIGHT

The apartment is a typical developer cave: monitors everywhere, RGB lighting, empty energy drink cans stacked like a modern art installation.

Jordan sits at a standing desk, three monitors displaying code, design mockups, and a reference site: youmescript.com.

Jordan studies the reference intently.

                    JORDAN
      Okay, so they use real pages. White 
      rectangles on gray background. US 
      Letter size. One and a half inch 
      left margin...

Jordan types furiously. CSS code streams across one monitor.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Courier Prime font. Monospace. Twelve 
      point. Line height of sixteen pixels...

The code compiles. Jordan refreshes a browser window. A beautiful page layout appears - white rectangle on gray background.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Yes! Now the pagination...

Jordan scrolls through the editor. Pages flow seamlessly with gaps between them.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Fifty-five lines per page. Automatic 
      page breaks. Page numbers on the 
      right...

Jordan implements the page numbering logic. The numbers appear in the top right corner, starting from page two (after the title page).

Jordan leans back, satisfied.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Now for the hard part. The text 
      input.

CUT TO:

INT. JORDAN'S APARTMENT - LATER THAT NIGHT

The clock shows 3:47 AM. Jordan's eyes are bloodshot but focused.

Jordan stares at the screen, where text jumps around erratically as they type.

                    JORDAN
      No, no, no. The cursor can't jump 
      like that. It has to stay stable. 
      Professional editors don't have 
      bouncing text.

Jordan opens Fountain.io documentation, studies the syntax rules.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Scene headings start with INT or 
      EXT. Character names are all caps. 
      Dialogue is indented...

Jordan implements the Fountain parser. The editor now automatically detects element types.

Jordan tests the Tab key. The text cycles through Scene Heading, Action, Character, Dialogue, Parenthetical, Transition.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
      Tab to cycle elements. Enter to 
      advance to the next logical element. 
      Scene heading goes to action. 
      Character goes to dialogue. Dialogue 
      goes back to action...

Jordan tests it. It works perfectly.

                    JORDAN (CONT'D)
          (relieved)
      Finally. Text input that doesn't 
      make me want to throw my computer 
      out the window.

Jordan saves the code, commits to git.

FADE TO:

INT. COFFEE SHOP - DAY (WEEKS LATER)

The same coffee shop, but Jordan looks different: more confident, well-rested, wearing a ClawScreenwriter t-shirt they had made.

Jordan sits across from MIRA (30s, professional, carrying a leather portfolio). Mira opens the portfolio, revealing printed screenplay pages.

                    MIRA
      I've been using Final Draft for 
      fifteen years. I'm not easily 
      impressed.

Jordan slides their laptop across the table. The screen shows ClawScreenwriter with a beautiful screenplay loaded.

                    JORDAN
      Try it. Write something.

Mira hesitates, then types. A scene heading appears. Mira hits Enter. The cursor moves to action lines. Mira types dialogue. The formatting is automatic.

Mira's eyes widen.

                    MIRA
      The pagination... it's perfect. Real 
      screenplay pages. And the title page 
      is separate?

                    JORDAN
      Always. Script content starts on 
      page two. Just like the pros.

Mira continues typing, testing different elements. Parentheticals indent correctly. Transitions align right.

                    MIRA
          (impressed)
      And you built this yourself?

                    JORDAN
      Well, I had some help. The OpenClaw 
      framework. Modern web tech. But yeah, 
      mostly me. Lots of late nights.

Mira exports the script to PDF. The export looks professional, industry-standard formatting.

                    MIRA
      The export is clean. No weird 
      formatting issues. My agent could 
      submit this tomorrow.

Jordan smiles.

                    JORDAN
      That's the goal. Professional tools 
      for professional writers. Without 
      the professional price tag.

Mira closes the laptop, slides it back.

                    MIRA
      I'm in. When can I start using this 
      for my next project?

                    JORDAN
      It's live now. ClawScreenwriter.app.

Mira makes a note in their phone.

                    MIRA
      You know what the best part is?

                    JORDAN
      The automatic formatting?

                    MIRA
      No. The fact that it doesn't look 
      like it was designed in 1998. Finally, 
      a screenplay app that understands 
      aesthetics matter.

Jordan beams.

                    JORDAN
      That was the whole point. Writers 
      spend hours staring at their screens. 
      It should be beautiful.

FADE TO:

EXT. CITY SKYLINE - SUNSET

The Seattle skyline glows orange. We see the coffee shop from outside, Jordan and Mira visible through the window, talking animatedly.

SUPER: "ClawScreenwriter is now used by writers in over 40 countries"

FADE OUT.

THE END